    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-03T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-03T08:00:00-05:00" n="420"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d420">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/5–354</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">United States Delegation</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-03T14:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 3, 1954—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Secto1">Secto</gloss> 76. Repeated information Paris 172.
                        <persName corresp="#p_CJ1">Chauvel</persName> states that French delegation
                    is working hard on proposal to be put forward at Geneva conference re Laos,
                    Cambodia and Vietnam.<note n="1" xml:id="d420fn1">The U.S. Delegation informed
                        the Department of State that same day in telegram <gloss target="#t_Secto1"
                            >Secto</gloss> 81 that the French hoped to be in a position to introduce
                        the proposal with U.S. support or at least U.S. approval at the beginning of
                        the Indochina phase. (396.1 GE/5–354)</note> He said French wished to
                    separate out the Laos and Cambodia question from that of Vietnam so that status
                    of Laos and Cambodia will not be compromised by infinitely more difficult
                    problem of Vietnam. He said that as soon as French had their thoughts in
                    reasonable shape they would wish to discuss them with General <persName
                        corresp="#p_SWB1">Smith</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d420fn2">Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> departed Geneva for Washington May 3; Under Secretary
                            <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">Walter Bedell Smith</persName> succeeded the
                        Secretary as head of the U.S. Delegation.</note> and this might be <pb
                        facs="0705" n="679" xml:id="pg_679"/> possible in next day or so. He felt it
                    would certainly be possible to go over with us their position with respect to
                    Laos and Cambodia not later than tomorrow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
